The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, April 07, 2004 				 FDI worth Rs 617 cr cleared 
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 																								New Delhi, April 6: The government has cleared 34 foreign direct investment (FDI) proposals, worth Rs 617.28 crore, including proposals for foreign investments in Zee Telefilms and Business Standard. 																								Subash Chandra-owned Zee Telefilms has been allowed to issue Rs 480 crore foreign currency convertible bonds (FCCBs) to two foreign companies. 																								Pearson Overseas Holdings of the UK has been permitted to pick up a 13.85 per cent stake in the financial daily, Business Standard, for Rs 8.37 crore.																								Zee Telefilms plans to issue FCCBs worth Rs 480 crore to Virgin Island-based Delgrada Limited and Wakefield Holdings of Mauritius, officials said.																								Mauritius-based Tiara Investment has been permitted to raise its stake from 32.5 per cent to 59 per cent in DCM Estates and Infrastructure Limited. 																								Another company from Mauritius, Covanta Energy, plans to increase its equity in its Indian arm Great Eastern Energy Corporation from 50 to 100 per cent with an investment of Rs 20 crore.																								Lafarge Refractories of France and Clipsal Investment Pte of Mauritius have received the governments approval for conversion of external commercial borrowing of their Indian arms into equity.																								The proposals, which were approved by finance minister Jaswant Singh, includes that of Citicorp International Finance to raise its stake in Monnet Ispat from 5.4 to per cent 19.56 per cent for Rs 35.27 crore.																								German company Ri Metering Gmbh has been allowed to invest Rs 40.80 crore in its Indian arm Elster Metering.																								Most of the proposals that came up for clearance from finance ministry pertains to information technology and broadcasting, petroleum, steel, urban employment and poverty alleviation.
